<DOC><DOCNO> AP900613-0207 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-90 0736EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a PM-ThePersuaders-CorporateLimits Adv27   06-13 0195</FIRST><SECOND>PM-The Persuaders-Corporate Limits, Adv 27,0210</SECOND><NOTE>$adv27</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Wednesday PMs, June 27, and thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>16 States Limit Corporate Campaign Donations; 20 Bar Them</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-The Persuaders III</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Twenty states bar corporations from making campaigncontributions to legislative candidates. Of the 30 that allowbusiness donations, 16 set maximums on contributions to individualcandidates.   Some of the states have maximums for a calendar year and someset limits per election, whether primary, runoff or generalelection.   Here are the limits:   _Alabama: $500 per election.   _Alaska: $1,000 per year.   _Arkansas: $1,500 per election.   _California: $1,000 per fiscal year (primary and generalelection are in different fiscal years).   _Delaware: $500 per election.   _Florida: $1,000 per election.   _Hawaii: $2,000 per election.   _Indiana: $2,000 per year.   _Kansas: $500 per House election, $1,000 per Senate election.   _Louisiana: $2,500 per election.   _Maine: $5,000 per election.   _Maryland: $1,000 per election; $2,500 for all donations.   _Mississippi: $1,000 per election.   _New York: $2,500-$3,396 per House election depending ondistrict, $4,000-$5,000 per Senate election; $5,000 per year forall donations.   _Rhode Island: $2,000 per year.   _Vermont: $1,000 per year; $2,000 for all donations.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Wednesday PMs, June 27</NOTE></DOC>